    <exercise id="fs-id1350363" type="problems-exercises"><problem id="fs-id1350364">    <para id="import-auto-id2602267">Find the ratio of speeds of an electron and a negative hydrogen ion (one having an extra electron) accelerated through the same voltage, assuming non-relativistic final speeds. Take the mass of the hydrogen ion to be <m:math><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mn>1</m:mn><m:mtext>.</m:mtext><m:mtext>67</m:mtext><m:mi>×</m:mi><m:msup><m:mtext>10</m:mtext><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mo stretchy="false">–</m:mo><m:mtext>27</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:msup><m:mspace width="0.25em"/><m:mtext> kg</m:mtext><m:mtext>.</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:math></para></problem>
<solution id="eip-id2393274">
<para id="eip-id2393276">42.8</para>
</solution></exercise><exercise id="fs-id2607118" type="problems-exercises"><problem id="fs-id2607119">    <para id="import-auto-id2657982">An evacuated tube uses an accelerating voltage of 40 kV to accelerate electrons to hit a copper plate and produce x rays.  Non-relativistically, what would be the maximum speed of these electrons?  </para></problem></exercise>
    <exercise id="fs-id2595258" type="problems-exercises"><problem id="fs-id2595259">    <para id="import-auto-id2694260">A bare helium nucleus has two positive charges and a mass of <m:math><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mn>6</m:mn><m:mtext>.</m:mtext><m:mtext>64</m:mtext><m:mi> × </m:mi><m:msup><m:mtext>10</m:mtext><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mtext>–27</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:msup><m:mspace width="0.25em"/><m:mtext> kg</m:mtext><m:mtext>.</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:math> (a) Calculate its kinetic energy in joules at 2.00% of the speed of light. (b) What is this in electron volts? (c) What voltage would be needed to obtain this energy?</para></problem></exercise>
    <exercise id="fs-id2574445" type="problems-exercises"><problem id="fs-id2574446">
<para id="eip-id1972816"><title>Integrated Concepts</title> </para>

<para id="import-auto-id2694470" fo:font-weight="normal">Singly charged gas ions are accelerated from rest through a voltage of 13.0 V. At what temperature will the average kinetic energy of gas molecules be the same as that given these ions? </para>
    </problem>
<solution id="fs-id2574052">
    <para id="import-auto-id2694479"><m:math>
        
          <m:mrow>

