    </exercise><exercise id="fs-id1362960" type="problems-exercises"><problem id="fs-id1362962"> <para id="eip-id1759475"> <title>Integrated Concepts</title> </para>  <para id="import-auto-id2694668">Fusion probability is greatly enhanced when appropriate nuclei are brought close together, but mutual Coulomb repulsion must be overcome. This can be done using the kinetic energy of high-temperature gas ions or by accelerating the nuclei toward one another. (a) Calculate the potential energy of two singly charged nuclei separated by <m:math><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mn>1</m:mn><m:mtext>.</m:mtext><m:mtext>00</m:mtext><m:mi>×</m:mi><m:msup><m:mtext>10</m:mtext><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mtext>–12</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:msup><m:mspace width="0.25em"/><m:mtext> m</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:math> by finding the voltage of one at that distance and multiplying by the charge of the other. (b) At what temperature will atoms of a gas have an average kinetic energy equal to this needed electrical potential energy?</para></problem></exercise><exercise id="fs-id2723641" type="problems-exercises"><problem id="fs-id2723642"> <para id="eip-id2898897"><title>Unreasonable Results</title>   </para><para id="import-auto-id2693464">(a) Find the voltage near a 10.0 cm diameter metal sphere that has 8.00 C of excess positive charge on it. (b) What is unreasonable about this result? (c) Which assumptions are responsible?</para>
